---
import DocsLayout from "~/layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import Code from "~/components/Code.astro";
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Effects & purity"
  current="effects"
  description="Purity, foul, and the ? operator in kex."
>
  <h1>Effects & purity</h1>

  <p>
    Functions are pure by default. To perform side effects — read a file, print,
    spawn a process — you mark a function <code>foul</code>. <strong
      >Pure code cannot call foul code</strong
    >, enforced at type-check time. The shape of the program tells you where IO
    happens.
  </p>

  <h2>Pure vs foul</h2>
  <Code
    code={`let compute(x: Int) = x * 2 + 1     # pure

foul readConfig(path: String) do
  return File.read(path)
end

# Compile error: pure code cannot call foul code.
# let bad(path: String) = readConfig(path)`}
    file="purity.kex"
    source="examples/purity.kex"
  />

  <p>
    <code>main</code> is implicitly foul, so programs still have a natural place for
    IO.
  </p>

  <h2>Local mutation</h2>
  <p>
    Bindings are immutable by default. <code>var</code> opts into local mutation,
    and <code>!</code> rebinds the variable to the method’s updated return value —
    the underlying value is never mutated in place, so aliases never see the change.
  </p>
  <Code
    code={`var list = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
list.push!(6)
list.filter!(&.even?)
list.map! { |x| x * 10 }
# list is [20, 40, 60]

# frozen.push!(4)
# runtime error: Cannot use '!' on immutable binding: frozen`}
    file="mutation.kex"
    source="examples/mutation.kex"
  />
</DocsLayout>
